            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Daniel Shapiro\u2019s story begins not in Korea, where he was born, but in the foggy avenues of San Francisco\u2019s Sunset District. Adopted as an infant by a loving, progressive Jewish-American couple, Daniel\u2019s upbringing was a unique blend of cultures. He remembers Shabbat dinners with challah and brisket, alongside weekend trips to Japantown for Korean groceries his parents sought out to help him connect with his heritage. Despite their love, Daniel felt like an outsider, navigating the complex identity of being a Korean kid with a Jewish last name in a city of defined enclaves.\n\nThis feeling of displacement shadowed his educational journey. While bright, he was unfocused in high school, his energy consumed by internal questions of belonging. He scraped by with a diploma but had no interest in college, a decision that worried his academic-minded parents. His early twenties were a difficult, aimless period marked by bouts of deep depression and working odd jobs. The turning point came at 25, when, at his lowest, he sought help at a community mental health clinic in the Mission. There, for the first time, he was paired with a peer support specialist\u2014someone who had walked a similar path and could offer guidance born from experience, not a textbook.\n\nThat connection saved him. It gave him a language for his struggles and a map for recovery. Inspired, Daniel found his calling. He earned his GED and pursued certification as a Peer Support Specialist. Now, at 42, his life has a quiet, profound purpose. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond and takes the 38-Geary bus every morning to a non-profit where he helps young adults navigate the same mental health systems that once confounded him. His lived experience is his greatest credential.\n\nHis social circle is small but deep, consisting of a few close friends and his aging parents, with whom he is now very close. Daniel\u2019s dream isn\u2019t wealth or status; it\u2019s the quiet satisfaction of seeing someone he\u2019s helped find their footing. His connection to San Francisco is etched into its sidewalks and Muni lines\u2014a city that challenged, broke, and ultimately rebuilt him into a force for quiet, compassionate change."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s eight, and the smell of his mom's brisket fills their Sunset home. She lights the Shabbat candles, her face glowing. He catches his reflection in the dark window\u2014a small Korean boy outlined by the halo of a Jewish ritual. In that single moment, he feels two things at once: a deep, unconditional love for his family, and the first, quiet pang of being an observer in his own life. The feeling would follow him for decades.\n\n2.\nHe\u2019s a sophomore at Lincoln High. A substitute doing roll call pauses at his name. \u201cDaniel\u2026 Shapiro?\u201d She looks from the list to his face, the question hanging in the air. A few kids snicker. In that small, silent judgment, he felt his entire identity reduced to a clerical error. It wasn't malice, just confusion, but it was enough. He felt his face burn with a familiar shame and retreated further into himself, deciding it was easier not to be seen at all.\n\n3.\nHe\u2019s 24, walking aimlessly down Irving Street late at night. The fog is a thick, wet blanket, swallowing the streetlights and muffling all sound. He feels utterly erased by it, as formless and cold as the vapor itself. Huddled in his thin jacket, he leans against a damp wall, the grit of the stucco pressing into his back. It wasn't sadness anymore, but a terrifying numbness\u2014the feeling of being a ghost in the city that was supposed to be his home.\n\n4.\nHe's 25, sitting in a stuffy office at a clinic in the Mission. He expects more jargon and pity. The peer specialist, a man named Marcus, listens, then leans forward. \"It sounds like you're navigating without a map.\" For the first time, Daniel doesn't feel like a patient or a problem. He just feels\u2026 seen. The simple act of being understood by someone who\u2019d been lost, too, was the first handhold he\u2019d been able to grasp. Hope, unfamiliar and fragile, stirred within him.\n\n5.\nJust last year, on his daily 38-Geary ride home, he saw a young woman he\u2019d mentored. When they first met, she couldn't lift her eyes from the floor. Now, she was animatedly talking with a friend, laughing, her face open and bright. She didn\u2019t see him, and he made no move to interrupt. He just felt a quiet, profound sense of rightness settle over him. This was his version of success\u2014not the grand gesture, but the silent, steady evidence of a life finding its way back."
